description:
MongoLog's module and level settings do not get reset between requests. In order to demonstrate this, you need to make two requests. I can reproduce this by doing the following:

Create file 1.php with the following content:
{code:php}
<?php
MongoLog::setLevel(MongoLog::ALL);
MongoLog::setModule(MongoLog::ALL);

$m = new MongoClient( 'mongodb://localhost', array('connect' => false ) );
?>
{code}

Create file 2.php with the following content:
{code:php}
<?php
$m = new MongoClient( 'mongodb://localhost', array('connect' => false ) );
?>
{code}

In the directory with 1.php and 2.php, run (with php 5.4):
{code}
php -S localhost:8111
{code}

In your browser, now request http://localhost:8111/1.php and then http://localhost:8111/2.php. In both requests, logs show up in the output window. This does not happen for 2.php if you request 2.php first.

The following script demonstrates the problem:

{code:php}
<?php
$conn = new MongoClient;
$db = $conn->phpunit;

$collection = $db->some_table;
var_dump( $collection );

// $collection from now is an string rather than an object
$cursor = new MongoCursor($conn, $collection);
var_dump( $collection );
var_dump(is_string($collection));
{code}

When the MongoClient ctor fails it throws an MongoConnectionException without any real error code.

We could use the error code from the parsing api, but those numbers are already reserved so would need to be padded.

{code:php}
<?php
try {
    $m = new MongoClient("localhost", array("connect" => false, "bogus"));
} catch(Exception $e) {
    var_dump($e->getCode());
}
{code}
{noformat}
int(0)
{noformat}

Currently PHP documentation (http://php.net/manual/en/mongocollection.insert.php) for GetLastError on an insert states:
{code}
If the last operation was an insert, an update or a remove, the number of objects affected will be returned.
{code}

This is not currently the case for inserts as it will always return 0.

See: https://github.com/doctrine/mongodb/commit/3ef26207cfd3886ef115c454ee2142a63a334dc0

{quote}
The driver returns numeric types in getReadPreference() instead of the string constants accepted by setReadPreference(). This is likely a bug.

The format for tag sets returned by getReadPreference() differs from that accepted by setReadPreference(). This likely isn't a bug.
{quote}

Those are two inconsistencies, but I believe only the first is a bug worth fixing.

To quote discussion from another issue:

{quote}
All drivers rely on the [isMaster|http://docs.mongodb.org/manual/reference/command/isMaster/] command to determine the state of the replica set. This command needs to be run on each node connection, and will tell us if the node is a primary or secondary (both boolean fields), along with listing all other nodes in the configuration (regardless of their state). I believe the problem is default behavior in [mongo_connection_ismaster()|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/blob/master/mcon/connections.c#L560], which considers the node a secondary. I will need to confirm with my PHP driver colleagues, but my suggested fix entails reading the {{secondary}} field from isMaster's response and ensuring that is {{true}} before defaulting to secondary status. This also entails creating a new default status, such as "invalid", to mark connections (i.e. nodes) as unusable for queries.
{quote}

Since the new connection handling / MongoClient introduction there is no way to set if a query should run on a secondary per cursor (request), however the documentation does not mention this. In http:://php.net/manual/en/mongocursor.slaveokay.php it explicitly states that reads would go to secondaries, if conditions are met. Either the documentation should mention this or this should be fixed (unlikely, right?).

This prevents us from upgrading past 1.2.x, since we use this extensively. By default we have all finds go to the primary and then specify which finds should go to secondaries when constructing the query.

Here is a test I used:
{code:php}
<?php

$conn = new MongoClient('mongodb://mongo-data-prim,mongo-data-sec1,mongo-data-sec2', array(
	'replicaSet' => 'myset',
));

$col = $conn->test->members;

MongoCursor::$slaveOkay = true;
$cursor = $col->find(array(), array('email' => true));
$cursor->slaveOkay(true)->limit(1);

print_r(iterator_to_array($cursor));
print_r($cursor->info()); // always contains IP of mongo-data-prim
?>
{code}

If you provide a single op to MongoCollection::aggregate() it assumes you're providing an array of ops and breaks.

PHP dev work usually starts with verifying the output of a $match op, so it's unexpected to have Collection::aggregate(['$match'=>[stuff]]) throw an esoteric error code 13111 with a cryptic error text.

Fix Suggestions (worst to best imo):
1.Remove the list of ops and force aggregate to accept only a single array of ops.
2. Allow a single op to be provided to aggregate. pseudocode {
  if (count(args) === 1 && is_string(key(arg1))) {
    //follow list style invocation instead of array invocation
  }
}
3. Give pipelines a helper factory to generate a structure that aggregate() expects. Ala MongoDBRef::create(). Something like:
$ops = MongoPipeline::create(['project', [args]] , ...);
$coll->aggregate($ops);

4. Give them a full object wrapper, ala MongoCode, so you could type-check the aggregates and catch invalid ops or malformed ops prior to aggregate call.

$op1 = new MongoPipeline('project', [args]);
$op2 = new MongoPipeline('group', [args]);
$coll->aggregate($op1, $op2);

then if someone wrote:
$op3 = new MongoPipeline('nosuchop', [args]);
it would throw an error related to 'nosuchop' not existing instead of the wildly uninformative "exception: wrong type for field (pipeline) 3 != 4".

When running queries against sparse indexes using the PHP driver, performance is poor.

For example, running this query against 30 million elements responds instantly, using the mongo shell:

db.items.find({'sparse_field' : 22 }).explain()
{
	"cursor" : "BtreeCursor sparse_field_1",
	"nscanned" : 322,
	"nscannedObjects" : 322,
	"n" : 322,
	"millis" : 0,
	"nYields" : 0,
	"nChunkSkips" : 0,
	"isMultiKey" : false,
	"indexOnly" : false,
	"indexBounds" : {
		"sparse_field" : [
			[
				22,
				22
			]
		]
	}
}

On the other hand, running this in PHP instead: 
$db->items->count(array('sparse_field' => 22));

Will take about 15 seconds to run. Using find will crash after hitting the 30 seconds timeout.

Using:
$count = $db->execute("db.items.count({ 'sparse_field' : 22} );"); 
Will return the result instantly. 

The group function doesn't seem affected, as I was able to use grouping with instant results as well.

I have many indexes, so I have cut this to only show that it is sparse:

db.items.getIndexes()
{
		"v" : 1,
		"key" : {
			"_id" : 1
		},
		"ns" : "stats.items",
		"name" : "_id_"
	},
	{
		"v" : 1,
		"key" : {
			"sparse_field" : 1
		},
		"ns" : "stats.items",
		"name" : "sparse_field_1",
		"sparse" : true
	}
}

I marked this item as critical because it is not possible to use the find function on a sparse index on a large database without crashing.

