Timeout in the line 94 is the timeout used to reconnect.
It will be better to use timeout from constructor there (aka stack monitor->timeout).

If we try connecting to a replica set with a timeout set to 1 millisecond, it still connects. The following script (with a replica set running on testing3.sailthru.pvt):

<?php

date_default_timezone_set('America/New_York');
$start_time = microtime(true);
echo "[" . date('Y-m-d H:i:s') . "] connecting\n";
try {
  $mongo = new Mongo('testing3.sailthru.pvt:27017,testing3.sailthru.pvt:27018', array('replicaSet' => 'test1', 'timeout' => 1));
  echo "[" . date('Y-m-d H:i:s') . "] connected\n";
} catch (Exception $e) {
  echo "Exception: " . $e->getMessage() . "\n";
}

$end_time = microtime(true);
echo "[" . date('Y-m-d H:i:s') . "] time " . round(($end_time - $start_time) * 1000) . "ms\n";


Gives the following output:

[2012-03-27 20:36:20] connecting
[2012-03-27 20:36:20] connected
[2012-03-27 20:36:20] time 67ms

If the 1-ms timeout were being respected, we would have expected to see an exception being thrown.

This causes a critical production issue in that when a database or network is in a degraded state, the timeout does not get respected and the connection hangs for a long time, causing a series of problems -- but the above is hopefully a pretty simple and straightforward test case.
